308
00:31:46,535 --> 00:31:49,658
[SPEAKER_02]: that are treated really poorly, and it costs us more money.

309
00:31:49,718 --> 00:31:54,403
[SPEAKER_02]: So if we put the money in the right place, we can actually make savings.

310
00:31:54,583 --> 00:31:57,586
[SPEAKER_02]: I did that when I was a home care and trade union rep.

311
00:31:57,727 --> 00:31:58,928
[SPEAKER_02]: I know we can do it again.

312
00:31:59,168 --> 00:32:06,796
[SPEAKER_02]: But at the moment, we're hemorrhaging money because the money is being used in the most inappropriate way, and people are not getting the care they deserve.

313
00:32:06,836 --> 00:32:07,617
[SPEAKER_02]: That's my question.

314
00:32:07,717 --> 00:32:08,898
[SPEAKER_02]: All right, thank you very much indeed for that.

315
00:32:08,978 --> 00:32:10,179
[SPEAKER_02]: But Angela, I'm just going to raise your taxes.

316
00:32:10,199 --> 00:32:10,520
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you.

317
00:32:10,560 --> 00:32:11,901
[SPEAKER_07]: I'm just going to return to debt.

318
00:32:11,921 --> 00:32:13,723
[SPEAKER_07]: That gap has to be closed.

319
00:32:13,703 --> 00:32:14,144
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you.

320
00:32:14,164 --> 00:32:20,655
[SPEAKER_07]: We're anchoring all of our debate tonight in the questions that have been so kindly provided by our audience, which we're very grateful for.

321
00:32:20,976 --> 00:32:27,468
[SPEAKER_07]: It was clear, actually, when Dennis was posing that question, as I alluded to earlier, it's not just the NHS, of course, that he's talking about.

322
00:32:27,508 --> 00:32:28,810
[SPEAKER_07]: He's talking about a whole range

